+
+# Nelôxi Numbers — Canon Reference
+
+Nelôxi counts in **twelves**. This page is the current canon reference for numbers, fractions, clock time, and percent. It replaces the old change brief.
+
+## Digits
+
+| value | Nelôxi | value | Nelôxi |
+|---:|---|---:|---|
+| 0 | **nolô** | 6 | **xeç** |
+| 1 | **jedôn** | 7 | **sedôm** |
+| 2 | **dva** | 8 | **osôm** |
+| 3 | **tri** | 9 | **deveñç** |
+| 4 | **xtiri** | 10 | **deseñç** |
+| 5 | **peñç** | 11 | **elva** |
+
+Twelve is **düna** — the round number, the "ten" of the dozenal system.
+
+## Breakpoints
+
+| value | Nelôxi | meaning |
+|---:|---|---|
+| 12 | **düna** | one dozen |
+| 144 | **grosô** | a dozen dozens, one gross |
+| 1728 | **mīrô** | a dozen gross |
+| 12⁶ | **miljôn** | about 2.99 million |
+
+## Thirteen through twenty-three
+
+The first dozen after **düna** is fused into single words:
+
+13 **dünjôn** · 14 **dünva** · 15 **düntri** · 16 **dünxtir** · 17 **dünpeñç** · 18 **dünxeç** · 19 **dünsedm** · 20 **dünosm** · 21 **dündevç** · 22 **dündesç** · 23 **dünelva**
+
+## Larger numbers
+
+After the fused forms, numbers are built by bare juxtaposition from largest unit to smallest, with no connector and no hyphen:
+
+- **dva düna** — 24
+- **dva düna tri** — 27
+- **tri düna peñç** — 41
+- **grosô dva düna** — 168
+- **dva grosô peñç düna tri** — 351
+
+The fixed largest-first order keeps the number unambiguous.
+
+## Counted nouns
+
+After numbers above one, the counted noun stands in the **partitive singular**, not the plural:
+
+- **tri kalāt** — three fish
+- **sedôm pǟvôt** — seven days
+- **düna kūt** — twelve months
+
+## Ordinals
+
+Add **-tô**:
+
+**jedôntô** first · **dvatô** second · **tritô** third · **dünatô** twelfth
+
+Example: **Jedôntô pǟvôl** — on the first day.
+
+## Fractions and shares
+
+Fractions use the trade words **half** "half" and **dēl** "part, share." A fraction is **number + dēl**:
+
+**tri-dēl** third · **xtiri-dēl** quarter · **deseñç-dēl** tenth
+
+The thing divided takes the linking case:
+
+- **dünas half** — half a dozen
+- **rās tri-dēl** — a third of the money
+
+## Clock time
+
+Clock time uses **klôk** with the 24-hour clock. Hours are counted in dozenal numbers:
+
+- **klôk nolô** — 00:00, midnight
+- **klôk xeç** — 06:00
+- **klôk düna** — 12:00, noon
+- **klôk dünxeç** — 18:00
+
+Casual speech may add time of day, but the standard is the plain 24-hour number.
+
+## Percent
+
+Nelôxia keeps the **%** symbol but reads it dozenally, as a full gross: a dozen of dozens.
+
+- Formal: **pôkrosa**
+- Casual/slang: **krossi**
+
+**100 krossi** means fully certain, where 100 is base-12 — one full gross.
